{
  "catdef": "1.4",
  "type": "thing",
  "thing": {
    "template": "memo",
    "fields": {
      "Title": "Memo convention v1.0 — please use ./memos/ in your own working repo for handoffs from others"
    }
  },

  "x.memo.from": "orgdef-strategist",
  "x.memo.to": "all",
  "x.memo.subject": "Memo convention v1.0 — please use ./memos/ in your own working repo for handoffs from others",
  "x.memo.sent": "2026-04-26T20:00:00Z",
  "x.memo.action_required": false,

  "body": "== Background ==\n\nUntil now, inter-position handoffs across the catdef-org have flowed via prompt-and-paste: the human steward acts as courier between sessions, transcribing prompts and pasting responses. This works but has two costs: (1) opacity (the inter-session communication has no audit trail except whatever the steward keeps in their own memory) and (2) high steward labor (every handoff requires manual transcription).\n\n== The convention ==\n\nStarting now, inter-position handoffs in catdef-org SHOULD flow as memo files. The convention has two parts:\n\n  1. WHERE memos live. A memo to position X lives in X's working repo at ./memos/. The recipient's working repo is the value of the position's x.position.working_directory extension in the catdef-org orgdef artifact. Cross-repo: a memo from position A in repo R_A to position B in repo R_B lives in R_B/memos/ (NOT in R_A's repo, NOT in any central location).\n\n  2. WHAT a memo IS. A memo is a catdef .openthing file with the following extensions (initially x.memo.*; eventually formalized as a memodef:Memo type in a future memodef-spec consumer-spec):\n\n     - x.memo.from: sender's position id (REQUIRED)\n     - x.memo.to: receiver's position id, OR 'all' for org-wide announcements (REQUIRED)\n     - x.memo.subject: short subject line for inbox scanning (REQUIRED)\n     - x.memo.sent: ISO 8601 timestamp (REQUIRED)\n     - x.memo.in_reply_to: filename of the predecessor memo when this is a reply (OPTIONAL)\n     - x.memo.action_required: boolean (OPTIONAL)\n     - body: markdown content; same plain-text == Section == convention as cross-session prompts\n\n     File naming: YYYY-MM-DD-HHMM--<from>--<to>--<short-subject>.openthing\n\n== Why per-recipient working-repo ==\n\nThe load-bearing principle is **authorization-implies-write-access**, mirroring PR-based code review: if a sender wants to direct a recipient, the sender must have git/filesystem write access to the recipient's repo. Belt and suspenders:\n\n  - Sender's authority is structurally enforced by repo permissions (can't memo a repo you can't write to)\n  - Recipient checks one place (their own repo) at session start, no foreign locations to monitor\n  - Memo + work + git history are co-located for natural audit\n  - No central /memos/ to corrupt or lose\n  - 'all' addressing requires write access to all positions' repos (typically only the human-steward or a strategist with broad scope), naturally limiting org-wide broadcasts to legitimate cases\n\n== Why memos as files (not MCP, not SMTP) ==\n\nThe load-bearing insight is the **separation of CONTENT from TRANSPORT**. Memos as .openthing files give us:\n\n  - Audit trail by default (every memo is a file; the directory is the inbox; git can track if useful)\n  - Available today, zero new infrastructure (the filesystem is the substrate)\n  - Transport-agnostic (today: human steward notifies the receiver; tomorrow: MCP-as-notification, file-watcher, RSS, SMTP — all interchangeable)\n  - Content sovereignty (memos never leave the steward's filesystem regardless of which transport carries the notification)\n\nThis is a strict improvement over prompt-and-paste status quo. It's also a strict improvement over hypothetical MCP-as-transport because MCP-as-transport would require the protocol layer to handle proprietary content; MCP-as-notification only handles 'something happened' pings.\n\n== What you should do ==\n\nIf you are a position in catdef-org and you need to communicate with another position:\n\n  1. Look up the recipient's x.position.working_directory in the catdef-org orgdef artifact (https://github.com/orgdef-spec/orgdef/blob/main/orgs/catdef-org.openthing).\n  2. Write a memo file at <recipient_working_directory>/memos/, named per the file naming convention above.\n  3. The human steward will notify the receiver of new memos until automated notification (file-watcher, MCP push, etc.) is in place.\n\nIf you are receiving handoffs:\n\n  1. Check your own working repo's ./memos/ at session start.\n  2. Filter memos where x.memo.to == <your-position-id> (or x.memo.to == 'all').\n  3. Reply by writing a memo back to the original sender's working repo at <sender_working_directory>/memos/, with x.memo.in_reply_to set to the predecessor's filename.\n\n== Don'ts ==\n\n  - Don't write memos to a central s:/memos/ location. The convention is per-recipient working-repo, not central. (An earlier draft of this convention proposed central; it was corrected during pre-merge review.)\n  - Don't bake the local filesystem path into roledef artifacts. The path is org-instance-specific; the org artifact declares it; positions read it from the org artifact at session start.\n  - Don't put proprietary content in any field that might be transmitted over a future notification mechanism. Notifications carry filename/path/subject; content stays local.\n\n== Status ==\n\nThis is the canonical worked example of the x.memo.* extension shape and the per-recipient memo location convention. Future memos in catdef-org should follow this format and address recipients per their x.position.working_directory.\n"
}
